Rating: 4
After 4-5 days of reading all of the reviews of this recipe and allowing my pears to finally ripen, here's how I tweaked the recipe and how it turned out. I coated the pork tenderloin with olive oil, salt, pepper and chopped fresh thyme. I added a couple of teaspoons of olive oil to an oven proof pan and sauteed the tenderloin for approximately 3 minutes per side, adding the shallots and garlic for the last 3 minutes. I added the pears to the pan, along with about 1/2 Cup of pear nectar and 1/4 cup chardonnay and put the entire pan in the oven (at 475 degrees) for about 12-15 minutes - uncovered. When the tenderloin was removed from the oven, I put the tenderloin on a cutting board (covered) and the pear mixture in a covered dish and returned the pan to the stove and added the additional pear nectar (about 1/2 cup), chicken broth (about 1/2 cup) with the roux and simmered for about 5 minutes to thicken. I added that to the pear mixture and used it as a sauce for the pork tenderloin. It was wonderful. Hubster went back for seconds - and thirds. Definitely company fare. I can't wait to make it for company.

