This was a great weeknight dinner that would be good enough for company! I made a few minor changes: After searing the pork and putting it in the oven, I left the shallots in the pan and then added the pears. I didn't remove the pears after browning, just added the nectar/broth mixture to the pan, which allowed the pears to soften a bit and cook further in the liquid. When the recipe called for flour and butter, I made a slurry of cornstarch with a bit of the cooking liquid in a separate bowl, and then added it back to the pan. Keeping everything in one pan helped the flavors develop, and made cleanup a breeze too.

Rating: 0
RE Coccinella's comment that the temperature given for cooking the pork was too low and that "pork should reach 165 degrees". Not so. Cooking to a higher temperature was done to prevent infections of Trichinella, a parasite that hasn't been found in pork since the early 1940's. In the meantime, a much leaner pork is being produced, so without the additional fat overcooking leads to a very dry product.

